# Memory Executor Agent Proposal (V1)

## 1. Scope and Goal

Introduce a new scheduled agent that executes LLM requests on a cron-driven basis.

- Primary goal in V1: produce memory mutations through memoryd tasks.
- Non-goal in V1: direct writes to legacy `memory` subsystem (future extension).

The agent is intended for recurring autonomous jobs (for example, periodic research) and condition-based jobs driven by `todo` records in memory.

agent id: memory_executor

## 2. Agent Placement and Lifecycle

- Code location: standard agents directory, proposed path `src/agents/memory_executor/`.
- Agent is optional and must not be a hard runtime dependency.
- If agent folder/config is absent, the platform must continue normal operation (webui part must handle it properly, Memory Executor panel must be hidden).

Execution model:
1. Cron tick invokes base-agent hook.
2. Hook evaluates due jobs from DB.
3. For each runnable job, the agent enqueues memoryd work (not direct LLM execution in V1).
4. memoryd performs model call and memory mutation.

Resolved proposal for base-class hook contracts (applies to all agents):

- Add optional async lifecycle hooks to AgentBase:
	- `async def on_init(self, runtime: dict[str, Any]) -> None`
	- `async def on_cron_tick(self, runtime: dict[str, Any]) -> None`
	- `async def on_shutdown(self, runtime: dict[str, Any]) -> None`
- Default implementation in AgentBase is no-op for all 3 hooks.
- Orchestrator/Core keeps a registry of instantiated agents and calls hooks sequentially for all active agents.
- Hook execution errors are isolated per agent: log warning/error and continue with next agent.
- If an agent package is absent, it is simply not discovered/instantiated, therefore no hook calls occur.
- Direct agent-to-agent calls/imports are allowed when explicitly designed.
- External non-agent modules should avoid hard coupling to concrete agent implementations and should prefer orchestrator/adapter APIs.

Recommended invocation points:
1. `on_init` during orchestrator startup after agent instantiation.
2. `on_cron_tick` in cron runner for each discovered active agent instance.
3. `on_shutdown` during graceful app stop.

## 3. Runtime Architecture (V1)

### 3.1 Default/Only Mode in V1

- `memoryd` is the default and only execution backend.
- Agent run = one evaluation cycle that may create zero, one, or multiple `memoryd` queue tasks.
- Actual processing responsibility belongs to `memoryd` workers.

Normal zero-task outcomes (not an error):
- no configured tasks for this agent/envid;
- tasks exist but are not due by `period_sec`;
- todo-gated task is due for check but no matching todo record is found;
- todo record exists but current status/content rules say "skip" for this cycle.

Normal high-volume outcomes (also not an error):
- one evaluation cycle may enqueue many tasks (including hundreds) when many task definitions become due at the same time;
- tasks may belong to multiple `envid` scopes and resolve into different `muid` queues.

Operational expectation for high-volume mode (V1):
- enqueue is append-only and should not block on immediate execution capacity;
- actual execution fairness/ordering is delegated to memoryd queue semantics (including same-MUID ordering rules);
- cron evaluation should process due-task candidates in bounded batches using `max_due_tasks_per_tick` to avoid long single-tick stalls.

### 3.2 Future Backends

- Future versions may support legacy `memory` and other memory backends.
- V1 decision: do not introduce full backend abstraction layer.
- V1 uses a partial backend bridge contract: `memoryd` remains the only concrete backend, but agent code calls a small set of backend-facing methods that are backend-agnostic by signature.

Minimal backend bridge method set (V1):
1. `initialize(runtime_ctx) -> None`
2. `resolve_scope(task_row, runtime_ctx) -> { envid, muid }`
3. `build_request(task_row, todo_payload, runtime_ctx) -> request_payload`
4. `enqueue(request_payload, runtime_ctx) -> { queued: bool, task_id?: str, reason?: str }`
5. `can_enqueue_now(task_row, runtime_ctx) -> { allowed: bool, reason?: str }`
6. `health(runtime_ctx) -> { ok: bool, details?: dict }`

V1 mapping to memoryd:
- `initialize` -> memoryd service init/check.
- `resolve_scope` -> effective envid + resolved muid selection.
- `build_request` -> convert task + optional todo payload into memoryd enqueue payload.
- `enqueue` -> `memoryd.enqueue_update(...)`.
- `can_enqueue_now` -> execution policy checks (`idle`, optional queue/capacity checks).
- `health` -> lightweight backend availability check for diagnostics/UI.

This keeps V1 implementation simple while preserving a stable call surface for future backends.

## 4. Configuration Model

Agent config is under `agents.items.memory_executor` and can be overridden by envid effective config.

Recommended V1 config:

```json5
{
	"agents": {
		"items": {
			"memory_executor": {
				"enabled": true,
				"execution_policy": "idle",
				"max_due_tasks_per_tick": 200,
				"memoryd": {
					"context_types": ["semantic", "episodic", "summaries", "news", "news_memory"],
					"update_types": ["semantic", "episodic", "summaries", "news", "news_memory"]
				},
				"logging": {
					"log_llm": true
				}
			}
		}
	}
}
```

Notes:
- `context_types` and `update_types` are default sets and can be narrowed per task.
- Validation should drop unsupported values with warning logs (same policy as other agents).
- `max_due_tasks_per_tick` limits how many due task definitions may be evaluated/enqueued in one cron cycle.
- Recommended default for V1: `200`.
- `0` means "no per-tick cap" (use with caution on large deployments).
- If due candidates exceed the cap, remaining candidates are deferred to next cron ticks.

## 5. Execution Policy

`execution_policy` controls launch eligibility.

- `idle`: start only when no task is currently running for this agent; if openaix is used, also require positive capacity signal.
- `always`: ignore idleness and allow scheduling whenever due.
- `queue_aware`: allow start only if queue depth for target provider/model is below configured threshold. (to be implemented in V2)

precedence:
1. schedule-level override
2. task-level override
3. agent default config


## 6. Memory Usage Rules

- Reuse common memory access logic from base agent to avoid duplication.
- V1 supports memoryd only.
- Per-task narrowing of `context_types` and `update_types` is mandatory.

Example optimization scenario:
- News collector task reads `news/news_memory` and writes only `news/news_memory`.
- Excludes unrelated channels (for example, `episodic`, `summaries`) to reduce context size.

## 7. Tool Injection Policy

Each task may define tools forwarded to model execution backend.

- `null` -> do not override tools field (backend default behavior).
- `[]` -> explicitly disable tool injection.
- `["tool_a", "tool_b"]` -> allowlist only these tools.

Resolved semantics for `null`:
- `null` means "DO NOT SEND `tools` FIELD" in the OpenAI/OpenAIx request payload.
- This explicitly keeps provider-side default behavior.
- No empty array should be substituted for `null`.

## 8. Output Contract

Two output channels are supported conceptually:
1. Tool calls.
2. Memory mutations.

Primary channel in V1: memory mutation JSON compatible with memoryd mutation contract.

Resolved decision:
- `memory_executor` does not define an independent mutation JSON schema in V1.
- It reuses the existing `memoryd` mutation contract as the source of truth.
- Versioning/compatibility rules are owned by `memoryd`; `memory_executor` is a producer/orchestrator only.

## 9. Persistence Model (PostgreSQL)

Use project PostgreSQL.

### 9.1 `memory_executor_tasks`

Proposed columns:
- `id` bigint generated always as identity primary key
- `name` text not null (human-readable task name)
- `envid` text null (default runtime envid)
- `period_sec` int null (minimum seconds between launches)
- `todo_title` text null (trigger title in `todo` memory)
- `prio` int not null default 8
- `request_text` text not null (task request text)
- `provider` text null
- `model` text null
- `tools` jsonb null
- `context_types` jsonb null
- `update_types` jsonb null
- `execution_policy` text null
- `enabled` boolean not null default true
- `last_run_at` timestamptz null
- `created_at` timestamptz not null default now()
- `updated_at` timestamptz not null default now()

### 9.2 `memory_executor_schedules` (Not in V1)

Complex conditions are deferred.

Resolved decision:
- Do not create `memory_executor_schedules` table in V1 migrations.
- V1 supports only period-based and todo-gated triggering from `memory_executor_tasks`.
- Advanced/compound launch conditions may be introduced in V2 (optional, not guaranteed).

## 10. Trigger and Run Semantics

Two scenario groups:

### 10.1 Pure Periodic Mode (`todo_title is null`)

- Launch every `period_sec` when due.
- No additional user payload is attached.

### 10.2 Todo-Driven Mode (`todo_title is not null`)

At due check:
1. Find memoryd `todo` records with matching title in effective envid/muid scope.
2. If no record found: do not run and reset timer window.
3. If records found: process records sequentially.

Per record handling:
- If record text is not valid JSON: run and pass raw text as user-context payload.
- If valid JSON:
	- if `status` is missing or not in `{done, cancelled, error}` -> run
	- if `status` in `{done, cancelled, error}` -> skip and reset timer window
- If JSON has `text`, pass it as user-context payload.

This allows tasks to self-complete by setting `status` or transferring control to another task.

Resolved timer reset semantics (V1):
- Reset timer after every completed evaluation cycle branch, except temporary-defer branches.
- Temporary-defer branch means "work was not performed due to potentially temporary reason".

Reset timer = YES:
- no matching todo record found;
- todo record status/content indicates skip (`done`/`cancelled`/`error`);
- invalid JSON todo payload but enqueue attempt was made and accepted or deterministically rejected as non-temporary.

Reset timer = NO (retry on next tick):
- enqueue was deferred due to temporary conditions (for example, execution policy gate such as `idle` busy state, backend temporary unavailability, capacity/queue backpressure);
- evaluation batch hit `max_due_tasks_per_tick` and not all due candidates were processed.

### 10.3 Duplicate Enqueue Protection

To prevent repeated enqueue of the same logical todo work while previous one is still in queue/processing:

- compute deterministic `enqueue_key` per logical run candidate;
- compute deterministic `work_hash` from source todo content;
- pass `caller_tag = enqueue_key` and optional `work_hash` in memoryd enqueue request;
- before enqueue, check memoryd for in-flight task with same `(muid, caller_tag)` or same `(muid, work_hash)` in states `pending` or `running`;
- if in-flight exists, skip enqueue (treat as successful dedup, not an error).

Recommended `enqueue_key` format:
- periodic task: `mx:{task_id}:periodic`
- todo-driven task: `mx:{task_id}:todo:{todo_record_id}`
- fallback if todo record id is unavailable: `mx:{task_id}:todo:{sha256(normalized_title + "|" + normalized_text)}`

Recommended `work_hash` calculation (done in agent before enqueue):
- algorithm: `sha256`
- source string (exact, no semantic normalization):
	`v1|task_id={task_id}|muid={muid}|todo_title={exact_title}|todo_text={exact_text}`
- `work_hash` is optional in enqueue API, but required for todo-driven dedup in `memory_executor`.

Rationale:
- keeps idempotency stable across ticks;
- avoids duplicate queue pressure;
- preserves explicit per-task/per-todo identity across envid/muid scopes.

### 10.4 Required Memoryd Extension For Dedup

This proposal requires a small explicit memoryd enhancement:

- enqueue API:
	- add optional parameter `work_hash: str | null` (or generic `dedup_hash`, same semantics).
- persistence:
	- store this value in queued/running task rows (nullable column).
- lookup capability:
	- provide queue check helper to detect in-flight task by `(muid, caller_tag)` and/or `(muid, work_hash)`.
- recommended DB support:
	- index for fast in-flight lookup by `muid + caller_tag + status`;
	- index for fast in-flight lookup by `muid + work_hash + status`.

Behavior rule:
- if matching in-flight task exists, enqueue returns dedup result (`queued=false`, `reason=duplicate_inflight`) and does not insert a new task.

### 10.5 Memory Executor Codex Override

For `memory_executor` tasks, prompt source can be task-provided text instead of `memoryd.requests` mapping.

Contract:
- `memoryd.enqueue_update(...)` includes optional `request_text: str | null = null`.
- `memory_executor` passes task `request_text` (after placeholder resolution) as `request_text` payload text.

Memoryd runtime rule:
- if `request_text` is not null:
	- do not resolve `memoryd.requests`;
	- do not search `request_file` by `requested_types`;
	- use the task-provided text directly as mutation codex prompt.
- if `request_text` is null:
	- preserve existing behavior using exact `request_file` resolution.

Persistence impact:
- `memoryd_tasks.request_text` (nullable) to persist execution mode.

Rationale:
- `memory_executor` task text is the source of truth for executor-specific logic;
- avoids global config coupling for executor-only flows;
- keeps backward compatibility for all non-executor memoryd producers.

Naming note:
- implementation uses `request_text` naming for both `memory_executor_tasks` and `memoryd_tasks` override flows.

## 11. Integration Rules

- External services must not depend directly on concrete agent modules.
- Startup/cron integration points should call base-class registries and optional hooks.
- LLM logging should be centralized at shared layer if not already fully shared.

Lifecycle hook runtime payload contract (V1):

- Hook signatures:
	- `on_init(runtime: dict[str, Any])`
	- `on_cron_tick(runtime: dict[str, Any])`
	- `on_shutdown(runtime: dict[str, Any])`
- `runtime` is always a dict.
- Required keys for each hook call:
	- `hook`: one of `on_init`, `on_cron_tick`, `on_shutdown`
	- `agent_id`: current agent id
	- `envid`: resolved envid for this agent instance, or `null` for global/default instance
	- `source`: caller source string (`webui.start`, `core.cron`, `webui.stop`, etc.)
	- `root_dir`: absolute project root path
- Optional keys (when available):
	- `tick_ts`: UTC timestamp for cron tick dispatch
	- `trace_id`: correlation id for one dispatch cycle
	- `cancel_requested`: bool hint for graceful early stop (default `false`)

Runtime behavior contract:
- Hooks are called sequentially for all active instantiated agents.
- Exception in one hook must not stop dispatch for remaining agents.
- Unknown extra keys in `runtime` are allowed and must be ignored by agents for forward compatibility.
- Agents should treat missing optional keys as normal and use safe defaults.

## 12. API and WebUI (Memory Executor Tab)

WebUI adds a dedicated `Memory Executor` tab.

Capabilities:
- select envid
- list tasks for selected envid
- create task
- edit task
- delete task with confirmation

Template UX:
- Task request editor supports applying templates from agent folder `templates/*.md`.
- UI includes template selector + `Apply Template` action.
- Templates are not edited in WebUI in V1.
- On apply, template content is copied into task `text` field; user may edit that task text freely.

Placeholder support in template/task text (V1):
- both template files and task `text` may contain placeholders in `${VAR}` / `${VAR:-default}` form;
- before enqueue, agent resolves placeholders from `.env`/effective environment (same substitution model as project config);
- unresolved placeholders without default should produce a validation warning and skip enqueue for that cycle;
- future versions may extend placeholder resolvers beyond `.env` (runtime context, memory lookups, etc.).

Initial templates:
1. News seeker template:
	 - instruct periodic AI-news search
	 - store important news to `news`
	 - store source/resource list to `news_memory`
	 - include mutation formatting guidance
2. Orchestrator template:
	 - read incoming `todo`
	 - decide target downstream agent
	 - create reassigned `todo` item with title = target agent name

## 13. Validation and Safety Rules

- Agent must validate effective memory types against enabled memoryd types.
- Invalid per-task overrides are filtered with warnings.
- Tool policy must be explicit in stored task payload.
- Task execution must be idempotent as far as practical, especially in todo-triggered flows.

Resolved anti-duplicate strategy:
- use deterministic `enqueue_key` + `work_hash` dedup checks against in-flight queue state.

## 14. Suggested V1 Delivery Plan

1. Data model and migration for `memory_executor_tasks`.
2. Base-agent integration hooks for optional cron-capable agents.
3. `memory_executor` core service and due-task evaluator.
4. memoryd enqueue bridge (provider/model/tools/type overrides).
5. WebUI tab and backend CRUD API.
6. Template loader and initial 2 templates.
7. Tests: due-check logic, todo-json status rules, tools forwarding, API CRUD.

